  <text>
    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Cambridge Sunday</p>
      <p>Dearest W. I have but a moment today. The enclosed from the Hen this morning gives me great delight. (But she has changed her mind 3 times, only since I came to Cambridge).</p>
      <p>Charlotte continues to improve very comfortably. She means to write you a line herself tomorrow, about their being unable to go to</p>
      <p>Ockham. You will have already learnt from my Thursday's letter that they move quite in the opposite direction. I am very sorry for it, selfishly speaking.</p>
      <p>But all their plans appear to me to be judicious &amp; right. So I cannot grumble.</p>
      <p>I am going to Whewell's after Chapel this evening. He called by chance here yesterday; &amp; civilly invited me to call on him &amp; his wife this evening. I have</p>
      <p>been introduced too to Lodge the Librarian, &amp; to Joseph Romilly the Registrar General. Both very kind &amp; interested about you; &amp; extremely civil to me.</p>
      <p>No more, dear, today; but don't think me a negligent Avis.</p>
      <p>Pray send me 5..0..0.</p>
    </div></body>
